I'm not sure _if it should_, but there's no documentation anywhere to the contrary, unless I missed something.

_.repeat(string, n) concatenates the input string with itself on every iteration of the do-while loop, including the last iteration when the concatenated result will never be used. If n, or the the length of the input string is large enough, repeat will generate a "RangeError: Invalid string length" exception. Breaking before `string += string` in the final iteration would prevent exceptions in some cases.

``` javascript
do {
  if (n % 2) {
    result += string;
  }
  n = nativeFloor(n / 2);

  // guard against unnecessary "Invalid string length" exceptions
  if(n === 0) {
    break;
  }
  string += string;
} while (n);
```

